    <div class="post-67 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized tag-fat-loss tag-hormone tag-insulin">
     <h2 class="entry-title">
      <a title="How to lose fat on thighs?" href="http://losethighfat.net/2015/05/05/how-to-lose-fat-on-thighs/">
       How to lose fat on thighs?
      </a>
     </h2>
     <ul class="post-by">
      <li class="no-padding-left">
       <a title="David" href="http://losethighfat.net/author/dpaul/">
        By David
       </a>
      </li>
      <li>
       May 5, 2015
      </li>
      <li>
       <span>
        Comments Off
        <span class="screen-reader-text">
         on How to lose fat on thighs?
        </span>
       </span>
      </li>
     </ul>
     <p>
      This is a question asked many times but it may as well be asked of any body part. How to lose fat on my calves or butt or cheeks or belly? The body parts may be different but the issue is basically the same, excess weight being manifested in inconvenient places.
     </p>
     <p>
      For weight loss to occur you must expend more energy than you take in through food and drink. A healthy weight is maintained because there is a good balance between energy intake and the energy expenditure in the body. The amount of energy provided by food depends on the amount of food and the type of food (energy rich or low energy) that you eat or drink. There are three possible scenarios.
     </p>
     <ol>
      <li>
       The energy consumed is equivalent to the energy expended.
      </li>
      <li>
       The energy consumed is greater than the energy expended.
      </li>
      <li>
       The energy consumed is less than the energy expended.
      </li>
     </ol>
     <p>
      Everyone will find himself in one of these three categories and if you are like a growing number of us that will be number 2. The best way to reach and maintain equilibrium (number 1) is through a decrease in food intake and an increase in physical activity. Unfortunately the process is not that simple.
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       All Food Is Not Created Equal
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      The food that we consume can be broken down into protein, fat and carbohydrates. Each of these components is essential for a variety of functions and the following is a partial list of those functions. Protein is needed for the growth of new tissue as well as the repair of existing tissue and the manufacture of some important hormones and enzymes. Protein can also be broken down and used for energy by cells. Fat is needed for the assimilation of certain vitamins and cell membrane maintenance. Fat acts as a buffer between organs and also as an energy supply when there is no glucose present in the bloodstream to satisfy the needs of the cells.
     </p>
     <p>
      Of these nutrients carbohydrates are the most important in terms of this discussion. Carbohydrates are essentially sugar and provide the glucose that is the fuel for our cells. When glucose rises in the bloodstream as a result of digestion the pancreas receives a signal to release insulin. Insulin is the hormone that enables glucose to enter our cells and provide energy for metabolism. Once these energy requirements are met the insulin directs any remaining glucose to be sent to fat cells for storage for future needs. Simply put, insulin either directs glucose to be burned as energy of stored as fat. It is important to remember that glucose triggers the release of insulin into the bloodstream so no stored fat will be burned when insulin is present. This is how the body was designed to work and it is a great design for a primitive hunter/gatherer where scarcity is the norm.
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       Too Much of a Good Thing
      </strong>
     </p>
     <p>
      Our primitive ancestors needed to take advantage of the sweet ripe fruit and carb laden root vegetables of summer in order to build up a fat reserve for the coming winter. As such our bodies evolved a preference for these foods. Today our bodies are still hardwired with these preferences but we live in a constant summer of availability. Exacerbating this situation are the manufacturers of processed foods who are all too aware of our innate cravings and design foods to capitalize on them. When we constantly bombard our bodies with carbohydrates (sugar) the pancreas releases insulin to meet the challenge but our cells become desensitized to the insulin. When this happens the insulin directs the glucose to be stored as fat. The first stage of this insulin insensitivity or insulin resistance can be characterized by cravings for sugar and carbohydrates, low energy, and increased difficulty in losing weight.
     </p>
     <p>
      If you are serious about achieving and maintaining  proper weight you must take action now and adopt a plan that combines effective exercise with a diet that keeps blood sugar in balance. If you are not confident about formulating your own plan then I urge you to watch the presentation at
      <a href="http://tinyurl.com/m2kjgvx">
       http://tinyurl.com/m2kjgvx
      </a>
       . It is important that you view the entire video. The plan is based on sound scientific principles and has helped many rapidly lose unwanted fat.
     </p>
     <p>
     </p>
